					<item>
		<title>HOW YOU CAN SUPPORT</title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/bauman_portfolio/support-the-movement__trashed/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 07 Oct 2020 00:59:05 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://clapat.ro/themes/wordpress-test/?post_type=bauman_portfolio&#038;p=2622</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"background_color":"#ffffff","className":"row_padding_top white-section"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container row_padding_top white-section" style="background-color:#ffffff;text-align:left"><!-- wp:columns -->
<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column {"width":35} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:35%"><!-- wp:heading {"className":"has-animation"} -->
<h2 class="has-animation">My First Protest</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Vic Stizzi</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column {"width":65} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:65%"><!-- wp:paragraph {"className":"has-animation"} -->
<p class="has-animation">Since my first encounter with the force of the Black Lives Matter movement, everything after was one perfect fitting piece after the other.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>I was walking through Soho to get to the West Broadway area when a large crowd, just two blocks away, caught my attention. I stood where all the shopping stores had boarded up their windows, splashed with rebel art... staring at this (what I can best describe as) river of music bending at Canal Street. I could not help but gaze, amazed at the solidarity... And then... it happened.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>My feet, slowly, one after the other took steps toward the sound of excitement... I couldn't believe it. The sound of adventure... there was no plan at this point. The sounds... which were never heard outside my own rant whenever my boss needed an ego-boost and I was on the other end. Whenever the police needed to make quota and I was on the other end. Or whenever someone chose to be miserable over rebellious... and I was on the other-fucking-end... NEVER have I heard such angry youthism outside me. My feet... they walked... from that "other end".</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>As I gravitated to the crowd, I remember being behind them as they were on the street and I, on the sidewalk. Then I was in the street, slowly working through the crowd towards the center and slowly learning the chants - No Justice... No Peace! Wake Up! Wake Up! This Is Your Fight Too!! ONE! We are the People! TWO! SAY IT LOUDER! THREE! WE WANT JUSTICE! FOR! THE! PEOPLEEEEE!! I shouted with my fist in the air and now in the front of the crowd, witnessing the stars and planets which the night cast over whenever injustice shows its face! I became a planet revolving around the movement... and now front-row seated, witnessing the welcoming crowd of Occupy City Hall... AKA... Abolition Park.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:column --></div>
<!-- /wp:columns --></div>
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/container -->

<!-- wp:spacer -->
<div style="height:100px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2>1. Follow The Growing Movements</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.instagram.com/abolitionpark/" target="_blank">@abolitionpark</a></li><li><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.instagram.com/abolitionplaza/" target="_blank">@abolitionplaza</a></li><li><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.instagram.com/radicalpeoplesassembly/" target="_blank">@radicalpeoplesassembly</a></li><li><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.instagram.com/skateforchanges/" target="_blank">@skateforchanges</a></li><li><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.instagram.com/nycmarchers/" target="_blank">@nycmarchers</a></li><li><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.instagram.com/warriorsinthegarden/" target="_blank">@warriorsinthegarden</a></li><li><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.instagram.com/vocalnewyork/" target="_blank">@vocalnewyork</a></li><li><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.instagram.com/ourlivesmatternyc/" target="_blank">@ourlivesmatternyc</a></li><li><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.instagram.com/riders4rights/" target="_blank">@Riders4Rights</a></li><li><a href="https://www.instagram.com/suppercollectivenyc/">@suppercollectivenyc</a></li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2>2. Read</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>13th &amp; When They See Us (films by Ava DuVernay)</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><a href="https://www.akpress.org/areprisonsobsolete.html"><em>Are Prisons Obsolete?</em></a>&nbsp;(Angela Y. Davis)</li><li><a href="https://www.versobooks.com/books/2426-the-end-of-policing"><em>The End of Policing</em></a>&nbsp;by (Alex Vitale)</li><li><a href="https://www.akpress.org/abolitionnowakpress.html"><em>Abolition Now! Ten Years of Strategy and Struggle Against the Prison Industrial Complex</em></a>&nbsp;(Anthology; also available directly from Critical Resistance<a href="http://criticalresistance.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Critical-Resistance-Abolition-Now-Ten-Years-of-Strategy-and-Struggle-against-the-Prison-Industrial-Complex.pdf">&nbsp;here</a>)</li><li><a href="https://www.akpress.org/our-enemies-in-blue.html"><em>Our Enemies in Blue: Police and Power in America</em></a> (Kristian Williams)</li><li><a href="https://www.versobooks.com/books/2107-policing-the-planet"><em>Policing the Planet</em></a>&nbsp;(Anthology)</li><li><a href="https://www.haymarketbooks.org/books/952-who-do-you-serve-who-do-you-protect"><em>Who Do You Serve, Who Do You Protect?</em></a>&nbsp;(Anthology via Truthout)</li><li><a href="https://www.ucpress.edu/book/9780520242012/golden-gulag"><em>Golden Gulag: Prisons, Surplus, Crisis, and Opposition in Globalizing California</em></a>&nbsp; (Ruth Wilson Gilmore)</li><li><a href="https://newjimcrow.com/"><em>The New Jim Crow</em></a>&nbsp; (Michelle Alexander)</li><li><a href="https://books.google.com/books/about/Police_Unbound.html?id=xO_tAAAAMAAJ"><em>Police Unbound: Corruption, Abuse, and Heroism by the Boys in Blue</em></a>&nbsp;(Anthony V. Bouza)</li><li><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://thenewpress.com/books/prison-by-any-other-name" target="_blank"><em>Prison by Any Other Name</em></a>&nbsp;(Maya Schenwar and Victoria Law)</li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:heading -->
<h2>3. Stay Informed</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li><a href="https://openpolice.org/departments">Check Your Local Police Grade</a> + File A Complaint On Your Local Police Officer</li><li><a href="https://mappingpoliceviolence.org/">An Interactive Map Of All The Police Killings In The United States</a></li><li><a href="https://projects.propublica.org/nypd-ccrb/">Search NYPD Complaints by Officer Name or Badge Number</a></li><li><a href="https://www1.nyc.gov/site/ccrb/policy/data-transparency-initiative-allegations.page">Allegation Statistics By the CCRB</a></li><li><a href="https://www.nyclu.org/en/campaigns/nypd-misconduct-database">NYPD MISCONDUCT COMPLAINT DATABASE</a></li><li>NYC Settlement Claims Including NYPD Misconduct Settlement Costs</li><li><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_assassinated_human_rights_activists">List Of Protestors Murdered</a></li><li><a href="http://aworldwithoutpolice.org/">A WORLD WITHOUT POLICE</a></li><li><a href="https://populardemocracy.org/sites/default/files/Freedom%20To%20Thrive%2C%20Higher%20Res%20Version.pdf?utm_source=The+Appeal&amp;utm_campaign=7e659f983a-EMAIL_CAMPAIGN_2018_08_09_04_14_COPY_01&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_term=0_72df992d84-7e659f983a-58426795">Spending Billions On Policing, Then Millions On Police Misconduct</a></li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

					<item>
		<title>DIRECT-ACTION-WEAR</title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/bauman_portfolio/direct-action-wear/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 07 Oct 2020 07:00:05 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://clapat.ro/themes/wordpress-test/?post_type=bauman_portfolio&#038;p=2623</guid>

<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column {"width":20} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:20%"></div>
<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column -->
<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center","className":"lookbookIntro","textColor":"vivid-red"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center lookbookIntro has-vivid-red-color has-text-color">Our approach to fashion is both, practical and responsible. Products are made to order and all our garments are sourced from specifically Anti-Sweatshop initiatives. We give every customer the option of Comfort (economic), Durability (balanced), or "Armor" (Supima Cotton) - so you and I can sleep knowing just that much is going back to a healthier, smarter, and better future.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column {"width":20} -->

					<item>
		<title>WHAT YOU SHOULD KNOW</title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/bauman_portfolio/abolition-now/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 07 Oct 2020 00:30:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://clapat.ro/themes/wordpress-test/?post_type=bauman_portfolio&#038;p=2624</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"background_color":"transparent","className":"small text-align-center row_padding_top row_padding_bottom"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container small text-align-center row_padding_top row_padding_bottom" style="background-color:transparent;text-align:left"><!-- wp:heading {"align":"center"} -->
<h2 class="has-text-align-center">#AbolitionNow</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center">Delegitimizing the police is not only beneficial for those they target, but also for the police officer's families and police officers themselves. Not only do police officers have disproportionately high rates of domestic violence and child abuse, but they're also more likely to get killed, commit suicide, and struggle with addiction than most sectors of society at large. Let's create a world in which no one oppresses or is oppressed in which no one has to live in fear.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":67} -->
<div style="height:67px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:columns -->
<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column {"width":25} -->

<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column {"width":83.9} -->

<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","className":"blkText","textColor":"white","fontSize":"huge"} -->
<h2 class="has-text-align-center blkText has-white-color has-text-color has-huge-font-size">7 MYTHS ABOUT POLICE</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":49} -->
<div style="height:49px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4,"className":"blkText","textColor":"white"} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center blkText has-white-color has-text-color">1. The Police Exercise Legitimate Authority</h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"left","className":"has-animation","textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-left has-animation has-white-color has-text-color">In fact, the average police officer is not a legal expert; he probably knows his department protocol, but very little about the actual laws. This means his enforcement involves a great deal of bluffing, improvisation, and f your dishonesty. Police lie on a regular basis: "I just got a report of someone of your description committing a crime around here. Want to show me some ID?"</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"className":"blkText","textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="blkText has-white-color has-text-color">This is not to say we should unthinkingly accept laws as legitimate, either. The entire judicial system protects the privileges of the wealthy and powerful. Obeying laws is not necessarily morally right - it may even be immoral. Slavery was legal, aiding escaped slaves illegal. The Nazis came to power in Germany via democratic elections and passed laws through the prescribed channels. We should aspire to the strength of conscience to do what we know is best, regardless of laws and police intimidation.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4,"className":"blkText","textColor":"white"} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center blkText has-white-color has-text-color">2. The Police Are Ordinary Workers Just Like Us; They Should Be Our Allies</h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center","className":"has-animation","textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center has-animation has-white-color has-text-color">Unfortunately, there's a big gap between "should be" and "are". The role of the police is to serve the interests of the ruling class; anyone who has not had a bad experience with them is likely privileged, submissive, or both. Today's police officers know exactly what they're getting into when they join the force - people in uniform don't just get cats out of trees. Yes, most take the job because of economic pressure, but needing a paycheck is no excuse for evicting families, harassing young people of color, or pepper-spraying demonstrators. Those whose conscience can be bought are everyone's potential enemies, not allies.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center","className":"blkText","textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center blkText has-white-color has-text-color">This fairy tale is more persuasive when it is couched in strategic terms; for example, "Every revolution succeeds at the moment the armed forces refuse to make war on their fellows; therefore we should focus on seducing the police on our side." But the police are not just any workers; they're the ones who chose to base their livelihoods upon defending the prevailing order, thus the least likely to be sympathetic to those who wish to change it. In this context, it makes more sense to oppose the police as such than to seek solidarity with them. As long as they serve their masters, they cannot be our allies; by denouncing the institution of police and demoralizing individual officers, we encourage them to seek other livelihoods so we can one day find common cause with them.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4,"textColor":"white"} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center has-white-color has-text-color">3. Maybe There Are Some Bad Apples, But Some Police Officers Are Good People</h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="has-white-color has-text-color">Perhaps some police officers have good intentions, but once again, insofar as they obey orders rather than their consciences, they cannot be trusted. One of the most human come-a-crosses is the EGO. On a good day, the officer ignores the smell of weed because it's too vague to know who it's coming from - but on a bad day, he's arresting a skateboarder for skating at the skatepark after midnight. There is no way to predict which are good or bad because the proven over and over again, officers are emotional human beings, and will take their bad day on you rather you happened to have a bad day or not.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="has-white-color has-text-color">There's something to be said for understanding the systematic nature of institutions, rather than attributing every injustice to the shortcomings of individuals. Remember the story of the man who, tormented by fleas, managed to catch one between his fingers? He scrutinized it for a long time before placing it back at the spot on his neck where had he caught it. His friends, confounded, inquired why on earth he would do such a thing. "That wasn't the one that was biting me". he explained.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4,"textColor":"white"} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center has-white-color has-text-color">4. Police Can Win Any Confrontation, So We Shouldn't Antagonize Them</h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="has-white-color has-text-color">With all their weapons, equipment, and surveillance, the police can seem invincible, but this is an illusion. They are limited by all sorts of invisible constraints - bureaucracy, public opinion, communication breakdowns, an overloaded judicial system. If they don't have vehicles or facilities available to transport and process a great number of arrestees, for example, they can't make mass arrests.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="has-white-color has-text-color">This is why a motley crowd armed only with the tear gas canisters shot at them can hold off a larger, more organized, better-equipped police force; contests between social unrest and military might don't play out according to the rules of military engagement. Those who have studied police, who can predict what they are prepared for and what they can and cannot do, can often outsmart and outmaneuver them.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="has-white-color has-text-color">Such small victories are especially inspiring for those who chafe under the heel of police violence on a daily basis. In the collective unconscious of our society, the police are the ultimate bastion of reality, the force that ensures that things stay the way they are; taking them on and winning, however temporarily, shows that reality is negotiable.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4,"textColor":"white"} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center has-white-color has-text-color">5. Police Are A Mere Distraction From The Real Enemy, Not Worth Our Wrath Or Attention</h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="has-white-color has-text-color">Alas, tyranny is not just a matter of politicians or executives; they would be powerless without those who do their bidding. When we contest their rule, we're also contesting the submission that keeps them in power, and sooner or later we're sure to come up against some of those who submit. That being said, it's true that the police are no more integral to hierarchy than the oppressive dynamics in our own communities; they are simply the external manifestation, on a larger scale, of the same phenomena. If we are to contest domination everywhere, rather than specializing in combating certain forms of it while leaving others unchallenged, we have to be prepared to confront it both in the streets and in our own bedrooms; we can't expect to win on one front without fighting on the other. We shouldn't fetishize confrontations with uniformed foes, we shouldn't forget the power imbalances in our own ranks - but neither should we be content merely to manage the details of our own oppression in a non-hierarchical manner.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4,"textColor":"white"} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center has-white-color has-text-color">6. We Need Police To Protect Us</h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="has-white-color has-text-color">According to this line of thinking, even if we might aspire to live in a society without police in the distant future, we need them today, for people are not ready to live together peacefully without armed enforcers. As if the social imbalances and fear maintained by police violence are peace! Those who argue that the police sometimes do good things bear the burden of proving that those same good things could not be accomplished at least as well by other means.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="has-white-color has-text-color">In any case, it's not as if a police-free society is suddenly going to appear overnight just because someone spray-paints "Fuck The Police" on a wall. The protracted struggle it will take to free our communities from police repression will probably go on as long as it takes us to learn to coexist peacefully; a community that can't sort out its own conflicts can't expect to triumph against a more powerful occupying force. In the meantime, opposition to police should be seen as a rejection of one of the most egregious sources of oppressive violence, not an assertion that without police there would be none. But if we can ever defeat and disband the police, we will surely be able to defend ourselves against less organized threats.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4,"textColor":"white"} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center has-white-color has-text-color">7. Resisting The Police Is Violent - It Makes You No Better Than Them</h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="has-white-color has-text-color">According to this thinking, violence is inherently a form of domination, and this inconsistent with opposing domination. Those who engage in violence play the same game as their oppressors thereby losing from the outset.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="has-white-color has-text-color">This is dangerously simplistic. Is a woman who defends herself against a rapist no better than the rapist? Were slaves who revolted no better than slave-holders? There is such a thing as self-defense. In some cases, violence enforced power imbalances; in other cases, it challenges them. For people who still have faith in an authoritarian system, following rules - whether legal or moral - is the top priority, at whatever cost: they believe they will be rewarded for doing so, regardless of what happens to others as a result. Whether such people call themselves conservatives or pacifists makes little difference in the end. On the other hand, for those of us who take responsibility for ourselves, the most important question is what will serve to make the world a better place. Sometimes this may include violence.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"textColor":"white"} -->
<p class="has-white-color has-text-color">Police are people too and deserve the same respect due to all living things. The point is not that they deserve to suffer or that we should bring them to justice. The point is that, in purely pragmatic terms, they must not be allowed to brutalize people or impose an unjust social order. Though it can be empowering for those who have spent their lives under the heel of oppression to contemplate finally settling the score with their oppressors, liberation is not a matter of exacting revenge but of rendering it unnecessary. Therefore, while it may sometimes even be necessary to set the police on fire, this should bot be done out of a spirit of vengeful self-righteousness, but from a place, if care and compassion- if not for the police themselves, at least for all who would otherwise suffer at their hands.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":210} -->
<div style="height:210px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer --></div></div>
<!-- /wp:group -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":67} -->
<div style="height:67px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer --></div>
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/container -->

<!-- wp:spacer -->
<div style="height:100px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"background_color":"transparent"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container" style="background-color:transparent;text-align:left"><!-- wp:heading -->
<h2>BUILDING A POLICE-FREE FUTURE</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->
<h3>FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS</h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>PRESENTED BY MPD150</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/accordion -->
<dl class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-accordion accordion undefined"><!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/accordion-item {"title":"Won't Abolishing The Police Create Chaos And Crime? How Will We Stay Safe?","content":"Police abolition work is not about snapping our fingers and instantly defunding every department in the world. Rather, we're talking about a gradual process of strategically reallocating resources, funding, and responsibility away from police and toward community-based models of safety, support, and prevention.\n\nThe people who respond to crises in our community should be the people who are best equipped to deal with those crises. Rather than strangers armed with guns, who very likely do not live in the neighborhoods they're patrolling, we want to create space for more mental health service providers, social workers, victim/survivor advocates, religious leaders, neighbors, and friends- all of the people who really make up the fabric of a community- to look out for one another."} -->
[accordion_item title="Won't Abolishing The Police Create Chaos And Crime? How Will We Stay Safe?"]Police abolition work is not about snapping our fingers and instantly defunding every department in the world. Rather, we're talking about a gradual process of strategically reallocating resources, funding, and responsibility away from police and toward community-based models of safety, support, and prevention.

The people who respond to crises in our community should be the people who are best equipped to deal with those crises. Rather than strangers armed with guns, who very likely do not live in the neighborhoods they're patrolling, we want to create space for more mental health service providers, social workers, victim/survivor advocates, religious leaders, neighbors, and friends- all of the people who really make up the fabric of a community- to look out for one another.[/accordion_item]
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/accordion-item -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/accordion-item {"title":"But What About Armed Bank Robbers, Murders, And Supervillains?","content":"Crime isn't random. Most of the time, it happens when someone has been unable to meet their basic needs through other means. So to really \u0022fight crime\u0022, we don't need more cops; we need more jobs, more educational opportunities, more arts programs, more community centers, more health resources, and more of a say in how our own communities function.\n\nSure, in this long transition process, we may need a small, specialized class of public servants whose job is to respond to violent crimes. But part of what we're talking about here is what role police play in our society. Right now, cops don't just respond to violent crimes; they make needless traffic stops, arrest petty drug users, harass Black and Brown people, and engage in a wide range of \u0022broken windows policing\u0022 behaviors that only serve to keep more people under the thumb of criminal justice system."} -->
[accordion_item title="But What About Armed Bank Robbers, Murders, And Supervillains?"]Crime isn't random. Most of the time, it happens when someone has been unable to meet their basic needs through other means. So to really "fight crime", we don't need more cops; we need more jobs, more educational opportunities, more arts programs, more community centers, more health resources, and more of a say in how our own communities function.

Sure, in this long transition process, we may need a small, specialized class of public servants whose job is to respond to violent crimes. But part of what we're talking about here is what role police play in our society. Right now, cops don't just respond to violent crimes; they make needless traffic stops, arrest petty drug users, harass Black and Brown people, and engage in a wide range of "broken windows policing" behaviors that only serve to keep more people under the thumb of criminal justice system.[/accordion_item]
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/accordion-item -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/accordion-item {"title":"But Why Not Fund The Police And Fund These Alternatives Too? Why Is It Either/Or?","content":"It's not just that police are ineffective: in many communities, they're actively harmful. The history of policing is a history of violence against marginalized-American police departments that were originally created to dominate and criminalize communities of color and poor white workers, a job they continue doing to this day. The list has grown even longer: LGBTQ folks, people with disabilities, activists- so many of us are attacked by cops on a daily basis.\n\nAnd it's bigger than police brutality; it's about how the prison industrial complex, the drug war, immigration law, and the web of policy, law, and culture that forms our criminal justice system has destroyed millions of lives and torn apart families. Cops don't prevent crime; they cause it, through the ongoing, violent disruption of our communities.\n\nIt's also worth noting that most social service agencies and organizations that could serve as alternatives to the police are underfunded, scrambling for grant money to stay alive while being forced to interact with officers who often make their jobs even harder. In 2016, the Minneapolis Police Department received $165 million in city funding alone. Imagine what that kind of money could do to keep our communities safe if it was reinvested."} -->
[accordion_item title="But Why Not Fund The Police And Fund These Alternatives Too? Why Is It Either/Or?"]It's not just that police are ineffective: in many communities, they're actively harmful. The history of policing is a history of violence against marginalized-American police departments that were originally created to dominate and criminalize communities of color and poor white workers, a job they continue doing to this day. The list has grown even longer: LGBTQ folks, people with disabilities, activists- so many of us are attacked by cops on a daily basis.

And it's bigger than police brutality; it's about how the prison industrial complex, the drug war, immigration law, and the web of policy, law, and culture that forms our criminal justice system has destroyed millions of lives and torn apart families. Cops don't prevent crime; they cause it, through the ongoing, violent disruption of our communities.

It's also worth noting that most social service agencies and organizations that could serve as alternatives to the police are underfunded, scrambling for grant money to stay alive while being forced to interact with officers who often make their jobs even harder. In 2016, the Minneapolis Police Department received $165 million in city funding alone. Imagine what that kind of money could do to keep our communities safe if it was reinvested.[/accordion_item]
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/accordion-item -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/accordion-item {"title":"What About Body Cameras? What About Civilian Review Boards, Implicit Bias Training, And Community Policing Initiatives?","content":"Video footage (whether from body cameras or other sources) wasn't enough to get justice for Philando Castile, Samuel DuBose, Walter Scott, Tamir Rice, and far too many other victims of police violence. A single implicit bias training session can't overcome decades of conditioning and department culture, Other reforms, while often noble in intention, simply do not do enough to get to the root of the issue.\n\nHistory is a useful guide here: community groups in the 1960s also demanded civilian review boards, better training, and community policing initiatives. Some of these demands were ever met. But universally, they were either ineffective or dismantled by the police department over time (look at the \u0022No Choke\u0022 Law and how quickly they cried to reform that law) It's time to try something new."} -->
[accordion_item title="What About Body Cameras? What About Civilian Review Boards, Implicit Bias Training, And Community Policing Initiatives?"]Video footage (whether from body cameras or other sources) wasn't enough to get justice for Philando Castile, Samuel DuBose, Walter Scott, Tamir Rice, and far too many other victims of police violence. A single implicit bias training session can't overcome decades of conditioning and department culture, Other reforms, while often noble in intention, simply do not do enough to get to the root of the issue.

History is a useful guide here: community groups in the 1960s also demanded civilian review boards, better training, and community policing initiatives. Some of these demands were ever met. But universally, they were either ineffective or dismantled by the police department over time (look at the "No Choke" Law and how quickly they cried to reform that law) It's time to try something new.[/accordion_item]
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/accordion-item -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/accordion-item {"title":"This All Sounds Good In Theory, But Wouldn't It Be Impossible To Do?","content":"Throughout US History, everyday people have regularly accomplished \u0022impossible\u0022 things, from the abolition of slavery to voting rights, to the 40-hour workweek, and more.\n\nWhat's really impossible is the idea that police departments can be reformed against their will to protect and serve communities whom they have always attacked.\n\nThe police, as an institution around the world, has existed for less than 200 years- less time than chattel slavery existed in the Americas. Abolishing the police doesn't need to be difficult- we can do it in our own cities, one dollar at a time, through redirecting budgets to common-sense alternative programs.\n\nLet's get to work!"} -->
[accordion_item title="This All Sounds Good In Theory, But Wouldn't It Be Impossible To Do?"]Throughout US History, everyday people have regularly accomplished "impossible" things, from the abolition of slavery to voting rights, to the 40-hour workweek, and more.

What's really impossible is the idea that police departments can be reformed against their will to protect and serve communities whom they have always attacked.

The police, as an institution around the world, has existed for less than 200 years- less time than chattel slavery existed in the Americas. Abolishing the police doesn't need to be difficult- we can do it in our own cities, one dollar at a time, through redirecting budgets to common-sense alternative programs.

Let's get to work![/accordion_item]
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/accordion-item --></dl>
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/accordion --></div>
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/container -->

<!-- wp:quote -->
<blockquote class="wp-block-quote"><p>We're asking cops to do too much in this country... Every societal failure, we put it off on the cops to solve. Not enough mental health funding, let the cops handle it... Here in Dallas, we got loose dog problem; let's have the cops chase loose dogs. Schools fail, let's give it to the cops... That's too much to ask. Policing was never meant to solve all those problems.</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><cite>Former Dallas Police Chief David Brown</cite></blockquote>
<!-- /wp:quote -->

					<item>
		<title>ABOLITION PARK, NYC</title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/bauman_portfolio/occupy-city-hall-abolition-park/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 07 Oct 2020 01:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://clapat.ro/themes/wordpress-test/?post_type=bauman_portfolio&#038;p=2627</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"background_color":"#ffffff","className":"row_padding_top row_padding_bottom white-section"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container row_padding_top row_padding_bottom white-section" style="background-color:#ffffff;text-align:left"><!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"background_color":"transparent","className":"has-animation"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container has-animation" style="background-color:transparent;text-align:left"><!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":1,"backgroundColor":"white","textColor":"luminous-vivid-amber","fontSize":"huge"} -->
<h1 class="has-text-align-center has-luminous-vivid-amber-color has-white-background-color has-text-color has-background has-huge-font-size" id="apsite"><strong><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="http://WWW.ABOLITIONPARK.COM" target="_blank">W</a></strong><strong><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="http://WWW.ABOLITIONPARK.COM" target="_blank">W</a></strong><strong><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="http://WWW.ABOLITIONPARK.COM" target="_blank">W</a></strong><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="http://WWW.ABOLITIONPARK.COM" target="_blank"><strong>.</strong></a><strong><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="http://WWW.ABOLITIONPARK.COM" target="_blank">ABOLITIONPARK.COM</a></strong></h1>
<!-- /wp:heading --></div>
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/container -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":70} -->
<div style="height:70px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:columns -->
<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column {"width":25} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:25%"></div>
<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column {"width":50} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:50%"><!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center","textColor":"black","style":{"typography":{"fontSize":21}}} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center has-black-color has-text-color" style="font-size:21px">Abolition Plaza began as a camp for the Occupy City Hall protest advocating for the defunding of the New York Police Department.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"center","textColor":"black","style":{"typography":{"fontSize":21}}} -->
<p class="has-text-align-center has-black-color has-text-color" style="font-size:21px">It has since become a mutual aid hub at the center of New York City where people protest systemic racism, celebrate Black life, and learn to take care of one another in the absence of the state.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column {"width":25} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:25%"></div>
<!-- /wp:column --></div>
<!-- /wp:columns --></div>
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/container -->

<!-- wp:core-embed/youtube {"url":"https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLLLhrtHx-9q2A_weYRVi1xBnmI_GErLXK","type":"video","providerNameSlug":"youtube","align":"center","className":"wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-embed-youtube aligncenter wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLLLhrtHx-9q2A_weYRVi1xBnmI_GErLXK
</div><figcaption>WATCH THE ABOLITION PLAYLIST</figcaption></figure>
<!-- /wp:core-embed/youtube -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":33} -->
<div style="height:33px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->]]></content:encoded>

					<item>
		<title>BLACK LIVES MATTER</title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/bauman_portfolio/black-lives-matter/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 07 Oct 2020 08:00:59 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://clapat.ro/themes/wordpress-test/?post_type=bauman_portfolio&#038;p=2628</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"background_color":"transparent","className":"row_padding_top row_padding_bottom text-align-center small"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container row_padding_top row_padding_bottom text-align-center small" style="background-color:transparent;text-align:left"><!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center">Black Lives Matter champions diversity. </h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center">While dealing with the existing corruption and discrimination, we the People, are further discovering what matters to the authoritarians of America…</h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center">and it is not us…</h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/container -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"background_color":"#ffffff","className":"row_padding_top row_padding_bottom white-section"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container row_padding_top row_padding_bottom white-section" style="background-color:#ffffff;text-align:left"><!-- wp:image {"align":"center","id":2901,"sizeSlug":"large","className":"has-animation has-scale"} -->
<div class="wp-block-image has-animation has-scale"><figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img src="http://www.yumyoda.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/BLM.png" alt="" class="wp-image-2901"/></figure></div>
<!-- /wp:image --></div>
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/container -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"background_color":"#f0002f","className":"row_padding_top has-animation dark-section"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container row_padding_top has-animation dark-section" style="background-color:#f0002f;text-align:left"></div>
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/container -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"background_color":"#f0002f","className":"small text-align-center row_padding_bottom dark-section"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container small text-align-center row_padding_bottom dark-section" style="background-color:#f0002f;text-align:left"><!-- wp:spacer {"height":50} -->
<div style="height:50px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4,"className":"has-mask"} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center has-mask">The United States was built by the People, but not for the People. </h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4,"className":"has-mask"} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center has-mask">The truth lives with us, whether hushed or heavy on our backs. And as technology grows with our children, it is increasingly difficult both to hide and to ignore the racism and discrimination that is everpresent in the systems that govern us. </h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":20} -->
<div style="height:20px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4,"className":"has-mask"} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center has-mask"><br></h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":20} -->
<div style="height:20px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4,"className":"has-mask"} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center has-mask">Black Lives Matter, being the initiative, is the very tip of the spear - titled Black Lives Matter. It is the sharpest most notably active under the regimes of Freedom, Liberation, and Justice. Supporting BLM, are the collective believes and demands OF THE PEOPLE. BLM is for Black Liberation but let's not ignore the truly inspiring and weighing possibilities. All Lives can not matter until Black Lives Matter. Due to the available technology and online education, people are becoming more independent, and thus less likely to keep silent about discrimination.</h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":75} -->
<div style="height:75px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center","level":4,"className":"has-mask"} -->
<h4 class="has-text-align-center has-mask">The movement itself has been removing the vale of deception where racism and white supremacy hide under. <br></h4>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":20} -->
<div style="height:20px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":20} -->
<div style="height:20px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer --></div>
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/container -->

<!-- wp:spacer -->
<div style="height:100px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:heading {"align":"center"} -->
<h2 class="has-text-align-center">YUMYODA VERSUS CORRUPTION</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"background_color":"transparent","className":"row_padding_top row_padding_bottom small"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container row_padding_top row_padding_bottom small" style="background-color:transparent;text-align:left"><!-- wp:columns -->
<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column {"width":35} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:35%"><!-- wp:heading {"className":"has-animation has-mask"} -->
<h2 class="has-animation has-mask">Police Misconduct + <strong>Br</strong>utality</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading --></div>
<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column {"width":65} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:65%"><!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Police brutality</strong> or <strong>excessive use of force</strong> by law enforcement can be legally defined as a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Civil_rights">civil rights</a> violation, where <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_enforcement_officer">law enforcement officers</a> exercise undue or excessive force against a subject. This may include but is not limited to, physical or verbal harassment, physical or mental injury, property damage, and death. In some countries, "the color of law" protects officers from ambiguous situations.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:column --></div>
<!-- /wp:columns -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/container -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"background_color":"transparent","className":"row_padding_top row_padding_bottom small"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container row_padding_top row_padding_bottom small" style="background-color:transparent;text-align:left"><!-- wp:columns -->
<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column {"width":35} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:35%"><!-- wp:heading {"className":"has-animation has-mask"} -->
<h2 class="has-animation has-mask">Malpolitics</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading --></div>
<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column {"width":65} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:65%"><!-- wp:paragraph {"className":"has-animation"} -->
<p class="has-animation">Forms of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corruption">corruption</a> vary, but can include <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bribery">bribery</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extortion">extortion</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cronyism">cronyism</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nepotism">nepotism</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parochialism">parochialism</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patronage">patronage</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Influence_peddling">influence peddling</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graft_(politics)">graft</a>, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Embezzlement">embezzlement</a>. Corruption may facilitate <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Organized_crime">criminal enterprise</a> such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drug_trafficking">drug trafficking</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Money_laundering">money laundering</a>, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_trafficking">human trafficking</a>, though it is not restricted to these activities. Misuse of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Government">government</a> power for other purposes, such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_repression">repression</a> of political opponents and general <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Police_brutality">police brutality</a>, is also considered political corruption.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:column --></div>
<!-- /wp:columns -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/container -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"background_color":"transparent","className":"row_padding_top row_padding_bottom small"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container row_padding_top row_padding_bottom small" style="background-color:transparent;text-align:left"><!-- wp:columns -->
<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column {"width":35} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:35%"><!-- wp:heading {"className":"has-animation has-mask"} -->
<h2 class="has-animation has-mask">Corporate Greed</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading --></div>
<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column {"width":65} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:65%"><!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>capitalism comes from various political and philosophical approaches, including <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anarchist">anarchist</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Socialist">socialist</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Religious">religious</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nationalist">nationalist</a> viewpoints. Some believe that capitalism can only be overcome through revolution while others believe that structural change can come slowly through <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reformism">political reforms</a>. Some critics believe there are merits in capitalism and wish to balance it with some form of social control, typically through government regulation (e.g. the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_market">social market</a> movement).</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:column --></div>
<!-- /wp:columns --></div>
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/container -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"background_color":"transparent"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container" style="background-color:transparent;text-align:left"><!-- wp:heading {"align":"center"} -->
<h2 class="has-text-align-center">"The Winning Initiative"</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":21} -->
<div style="height:21px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>The Black Lives Matter initiative respects those who've made movement in the past and learns from it. To neglect is to fail.</li><li>The Black Lives Matter initiative educates one's self and others when necessary. To force upon others is to fail.</li><li>The Black Lives Matter initiative will continue onward and forever "to find a way". To say "it's always been this way" is to fail.</li><li>The Black Lives Matter initiative goes through racism, like a spear, penetrating, and focused. To go around is to fail.</li><li>The Black Lives Matter initiative is ok with being imperfect thus adjusting. To repeat the mistakes and spread them is to fail.</li><li>The Black Lives Matter initiative knows what to fight for and what to compromise on. Neglecting this is to fail.</li><li>The Black Lives Matter initiative works hard and makes time. Being too busy for the movement is to fail.</li><li>The Black Lives Matter initiative is not afraid to lose. But to be afraid of winning is to fail.</li><li>The Black Lives Matter initiative makes commitments. Period. It is the government who makes promises... a failing system. </li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"align":"right"} -->
<p class="has-text-align-right">-Vic Stizzi</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>

					<item>
		<title>Sample Page</title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/sample-page/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 19 Feb 2020 14:36:58 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http:/?page_id=2</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>This is an example page. It's different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:quote -->
<blockquote class="wp-block-quote"><p>Hi there! I'm a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like pi&#241;a coladas. (And gettin' caught in the rain.)</p></blockquote>
<!-- /wp:quote -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>...or something like this:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:quote -->
<blockquote class="wp-block-quote"><p>The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.</p></blockquote>
<!-- /wp:quote -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>As a new WordPress user, you should go to <a href="http:/wp-admin/">your dashboard</a> to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->]]></content:encoded>

					<item>
		<title>Privacy Policy</title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/?page_id=3</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 19 Feb 2020 14:36:58 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http:/?page_id=3</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:heading --><h2>Who we are</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>Our website address is: http:.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>What personal data we collect and why we collect it</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --><h3>Comments</h3><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>When visitors leave comments on the site we collect the data shown in the comments form, and also the visitor&#8217;s IP address and browser user agent string to help spam detection.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>An anonymized string created from your email address (also called a hash) may be provided to the Gravatar service to see if you are using it. The Gravatar service privacy policy is available here: https://automattic.com/privacy/. After approval of your comment, your profile picture is visible to the public in the context of your comment.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --><h3>Media</h3><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>If you upload images to the website, you should avoid uploading images with embedded location data (EXIF GPS) included. Visitors to the website can download and extract any location data from images on the website.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --><h3>Contact forms</h3><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --><h3>Cookies</h3><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>If you leave a comment on our site you may opt-in to saving your name, email address and website in cookies. These are for your convenience so that you do not have to fill in your details again when you leave another comment. These cookies will last for one year.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>If you visit our login page, we will set a temporary cookie to determine if your browser accepts cookies. This cookie contains no personal data and is discarded when you close your browser.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>When you log in, we will also set up several cookies to save your login information and your screen display choices. Login cookies last for two days, and screen options cookies last for a year. If you select &quot;Remember Me&quot;, your login will persist for two weeks. If you log out of your account, the login cookies will be removed.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>If you edit or publish an article, an additional cookie will be saved in your browser. This cookie includes no personal data and simply indicates the post ID of the article you just edited. It expires after 1 day.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --><h3>Embedded content from other websites</h3><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>Articles on this site may include embedded content (e.g. videos, images, articles, etc.). Embedded content from other websites behaves in the exact same way as if the visitor has visited the other website.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>These websites may collect data about you, use cookies, embed additional third-party tracking, and monitor your interaction with that embedded content, including tracking your interaction with the embedded content if you have an account and are logged in to that website.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --><h3>Analytics</h3><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Who we share your data with</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>How long we retain your data</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>If you leave a comment, the comment and its metadata are retained indefinitely. This is so we can recognize and approve any follow-up comments automatically instead of holding them in a moderation queue.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>For users that register on our website (if any), we also store the personal information they provide in their user profile. All users can see, edit, or delete their personal information at any time (except they cannot change their username). Website administrators can also see and edit that information.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>What rights you have over your data</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>If you have an account on this site, or have left comments, you can request to receive an exported file of the personal data we hold about you, including any data you have provided to us. You can also request that we erase any personal data we hold about you. This does not include any data we are obliged to keep for administrative, legal, or security purposes.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Where we send your data</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:paragraph --><p>Visitor comments may be checked through an automated spam detection service.</p><!-- /wp:paragraph --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Your contact information</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:heading --><h2>Additional information</h2><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --><h3>How we protect your data</h3><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --><h3>What data breach procedures we have in place</h3><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --><h3>What third parties we receive data from</h3><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --><h3>What automated decision making and/or profiling we do with user data</h3><!-- /wp:heading --><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --><h3>Industry regulatory disclosure requirements</h3><!-- /wp:heading -->]]></content:encoded>

					<item>
		<title>About</title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/about/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 08 Jan 2020 19:57:03 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://clapat.ro/themes/bauman-wordpress/?page_id=2634</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:spacer {"height":40} -->
<div style="height:40px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"background_color":"transparent","className":"row_padding_bottom"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container row_padding_bottom" style="background-color:transparent;text-align:left"><!-- wp:columns -->
<div class="wp-block-columns"><!-- wp:column -->
<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"level":3,"className":"has-mask"} -->
<h3 class="has-mask">To Consume Good Knowledge &amp; Truth</h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"className":"has-animation"} -->
<p class="has-animation">We know what's out there, but it starts right here. Within you. Within me. Within us all - we have to resist giving in to the cycle of "fight and forget". Whatever happened to those before us, the Black Panthers? the Young Lords? Was it "Life" that happened to them... to the movement? Don't give in to the carrot of comfort. We have demands.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column -->
<div class="wp-block-column"></div>
<!-- /wp:column --></div>
<!-- /wp:columns --></div>
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/container -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/container {"className":"row_padding_top row_padding_bottom white-section"} -->
<div class="wp-block-bauman-gutenberg-container row_padding_top row_padding_bottom white-section" style="background-color:#f2f2f2;text-align:left"><!-- wp:heading {"level":1,"className":"has-mask"} -->
<h1 class="has-mask">Our Focus: Tri-Guerilla</h1>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:spacer -->
<div style="height:100px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:columns {"className":"has-animation"} -->
<div class="wp-block-columns has-animation"><!-- wp:column {"width":20,"className":"has-animation"} -->
<div class="wp-block-column has-animation" style="flex-basis:20%"><!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/icon-service {"icon":"fa fa-snowboarding","title":"Skateboarders","content":""} -->
[service icon="fa fa-snowboarding" title="Skateboarders" extra_class_name=""][/service]
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/icon-service --></div>
<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column {"width":80} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:80%"><!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>We look to support and amplify those who know what it means to take a stand. To take a stand in who you are, what you do, and why you do it. Rather one can demystify the phenomena of skateboarding or not, concrete surfing is in your blood... and in ours! Period!</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:column --></div>
<!-- /wp:columns -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":20,"className":"has-animation has-border"} -->
<div style="height:20px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer has-animation has-border"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":60} -->
<div style="height:60px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:columns {"className":"has-animation"} -->
<div class="wp-block-columns has-animation"><!-- wp:column {"width":20,"className":"has-animation"} -->
<div class="wp-block-column has-animation" style="flex-basis:20%"><!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/icon-service {"icon":"fa fa-bullhorn","title":"Activists","content":""} -->
[service icon="fa fa-bullhorn" title="Activists" extra_class_name=""][/service]
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/icon-service --></div>
<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column {"width":80} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:80%"><!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>SPEAK OUT LOUD! And say it with your chest. There is something wrong with the environment and we're not going to wait and find out what happens if nobody does anything about it. Change Is Near! and it is up to this generation to fight for that change. Who's world is this?? OUR WORLD!</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:column --></div>
<!-- /wp:columns -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":20,"className":"has-animation has-border"} -->
<div style="height:20px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer has-animation has-border"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":60} -->
<div style="height:60px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:columns {"className":"has-animation"} -->
<div class="wp-block-columns has-animation"><!-- wp:column {"width":20,"className":"has-animation"} -->
<div class="wp-block-column has-animation" style="flex-basis:20%"><!-- wp:bauman-gutenberg/icon-service {"icon":"fa fa-book-dead","title":"Street Installers","content":""} -->
[service icon="fa fa-book-dead" title="Street Installers" extra_class_name=""][/service]
<!-- /wp:bauman-gutenberg/icon-service --></div>
<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column {"width":80} -->
<div class="wp-block-column" style="flex-basis:80%"><!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Creativity for a cause. Get It Out There! Yumyoda supports the street artist of today when they can say a thousand words with one picture. How creative can you get? How far are you willing to go? And where would your message pop up next!? We want to feel it!</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:column --></div>
<!-- /wp:columns -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":20,"className":"has-animation has-border"} -->
<div style="height:20px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer has-animation has-border"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":60} -->
<div style="height:60px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>

					<item>
		<title>How To Fine-Tune Your Protester Mindset</title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/?p=2959</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 20 Aug 2020 00:35:48 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.yumyoda.com/?p=2959</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Are you a protester? Then you know more than anyone how stressful a day can be while its filled with a variety of strong emotions. Being aware of the day and how to manage yourself will help be efficient in this new lifestyle. Boom, right to it.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Delta waves </strong>(.5 to 3 Hz) are the slowest brain waves and occur primarily during our deepest state of dreamless sleep.<br><br>Pick a time like 11 pm to 9 am (or whatever) the more consistent you are with sleep and wake routines, your personal sleep cycle will adjust allowing you to hit Delta Waves easier. Delta Waves is the realm where many of your answers to our concerns come from. When you're coming up to new challenges, worrying about it doesn't help the urgency. What helps is getting to this part of your sleep!  </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":48} -->
<div style="height:48px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Theta waves</strong> (3 to 8 Hz) occur during sleep but have also been observed in the deepest states of Zen meditation.<br><br>This is a good place to rest energy, naps go from Alpha to Theta, and so listening to empowering speeches about the evolution of mind, man, and ambition can help shade or fine-tune your core-energy to a more appropriate vibration.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":48} -->
<div style="height:48px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Alpha waves</strong> (8 to 12 Hz) are present when your brain is in an idling default-state typically created when you're daydreaming or consciously practicing mindfulness or meditation. Alpha waves can also be created by doing aerobic exercise. <br><br>Create Art and/or Strategies right here! You can research art and strategies to feel inspired. A good place to start is to recreate (even if it's identical to the exiting) art or strategy. Draw It Out! Keep up a pattern of creativity during this stage to enhance it.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":48} -->
<div style="height:48px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Beta waves</strong> (12-30 Hz) typically dominate our normal waking states of consciousness and occur when <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/attention">attention</a> is directed towards cognitive and other tasks. Beta is a ‘fast’ wave activity that is present when we are alert, attentive, focused, and engaged in problem-solving or <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/decision-making">decision making</a>. Depression and <a href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/basics/anxiety">anxiety</a> have also been linked to beta waves because they can lead to "rut-like" thinking patterns. <br><br>In this state, you're marching, staying alert, and moving your feet! Balance Beta Waves by Chanting, Clapping your hands, and Stomping your feet to the beat! Please bring a drum or any musical instrument. You can also learn a chant you love, because listening to the other chants, you may feel like throwing it in the march when you feel the time is right. This helps grow in Beta.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:spacer {"height":48} -->
<div style="height:48px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>
<!-- /wp:spacer -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Gamma waves </strong>(25 to 100 Hz) typically hover around 40 Hz and are the fastest of the brain wave bandwidths. Gamma waves relate to the simultaneous processing of information from different brain areas and have been associated with higher states of conscious perception.<br><br>The only way here is by utilizing the other waves correctly. Gamma Waves are great for when being confronted and confronting opposition. Pro-Athletes get paid top dollar because of their ability to be here. You can do it too! This is a very unexpected experience and usually bestows itself onto you when you're in the middle of when you feel like your life is being threatened. The only way here is with confidence, sometimes when things happen faster than one's realization, you can get sucked up into Gamma. Be active and confident in your everyday activities, and know, you'll always safe because of this bad boy wave, right here. </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>
