					<item>
		<title>25 Ways To Kill Your Ego</title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/25-ways-to-kill-your-ego/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 14 Sep 2020 19:55:32 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.yumyoda.com/?p=3040</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The artist Marina Abramović <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="http://www.economist.com/node/17036088" target="_blank">has said that</a> the moment we begin to believe in our own greatness, that we kill our ability to be truly creative. What she is talking about is ego — the way that self-absorption ruins the very thing it celebrates. So how do we keep this toxic ego and selfishness at bay? How do we prevent ego from “sucking us down like the law of gravity?” The primary answer is simple: awareness. But after that, it’s a matter of hard work. In the course of researching Ego is the Enemy I was exposed to many strategies for combatting our arrogant and selfish impulses. Here are 25 proven exercises from successful men and women throughout history that will help you stay sober, clear-headed, creative, and humble. They work if you work them.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>1. Adopt the beginner’s mindset.</strong> </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“It is impossible to learn that which one thinks one already knows,” <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="http://dailystoic.com/Epictetus" target="_blank">Epictetus</a> says. When we let ego tell us that we have arrived and figured it all out, it prevents us from learning. <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://thoughtcatalog.com/ryan-holiday/2016/02/15-short-powerful-and-provocative-books-everyone-should-read/" target="_blank">Pick up a book</a> on a subject you know next to nothing about. Walk through a library or a bookstore — remind yourself how much you don’t know.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>2. Focus on the effort — not the outcome. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>With any creative endeavor at some point what we made leaves our hands. We can’t let what happens after that point have any sway over us. We need to remember famous coach John Wooden’s advice: “Success is peace of mind, which is a direct result of self-satisfaction in knowing you made the <em>effort</em> to do your best to become the best that you are capable of becoming.” Doing your best is what matters. Focus on that. External rewards are just extra.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>3. Choose purpose over passion. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Passion runs hot and burns out, while people with purpose — think of it as passion combined with reason — are more dedicated and have control over their direction. Christopher McCandless was passionate when he went “into the wild” but it didn’t work well, right? The inventor of the Segway was passionate. Better to have a <em>clear-headed purpose.</em></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>4. Shun the comfort of talking and face the work.</strong> </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“Void,” Marlon Brando once said, “is terrifying to most people.” We talk endlessly on social media getting validation and attention with fake internet points avoiding the uncertainty of doing the difficult and frightening work required of any creative endeavor. As creatives, we need to shut up and get to work. To face the void — despite the pain of doing so.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>5. Kill your pride before you lose your head.</strong> </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“Whom the gods wish to destroy,” Cyril Connolly wrote, “they first call promising.” You cannot let early pride lead you astray. You must remind yourself every day how much work is left to be done, not how much you have done. You must remember that humility is the antidote to pride.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>6. Stop telling yourself a story — there is no grand narrative. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>When you achieve any sort of success you might think that success in the future is just the natural and expected next part of the story. This is a straightforward path to failure — by getting too cocky and overconfident. Jeff Bezos, the founder of Amazon, reminds himself that there was “no aha moment” for his billion-dollar behemoth, no matter what he might read in his own press clippings. Focus on the present moment, not the story.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>7. Learn to manage (yourself and others).</strong> </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>John DeLorean was a brilliant engineer but a poor manager (of people and himself). One executive described his management style as “chasing colored balloons” — he was constantly distracted and abandoning one project for another. It’s just not enough to be smart or right or a genius. It’s gratifying to be the micromanaging egotistical boss at the center of everything — but that’s not how organizations grow and succeed. That’s not how you can grow as a person either.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>8. Know what matters to you and ruthlessly say no to everything else.</strong> </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Pursue what the philosopher Seneca refers to as euthymia — the tranquility of knowing what you are after and not being distracted by others. We accomplish this by having an honest conversation with ourselves and understanding our priorities. And rejecting all the rest. Learning how to say no. First, by saying no to the ego which wants it <em>all</em>.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>9. Forget credit and recognition.</strong> </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Before Bill Belichick became the four-time Super Bowl-winning head coach of the New England Patriots, he made his way up the ranks of the NFL by doing grunt work and making his superiors look good without getting any credit. When we are starting out in our pursuits we need to make an effort to trade short-term gratification for a long-term payoff. Submit under people who are already successful and learn and absorb everything you can. Forget credit.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>10. Connect with nature and the universe at large. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Going into nature is a powerful feeling and we need to tap into it as often as possible. Nothing draws us away from it more than material success. Go out there and reconnect with the world. Realize how small you are in relation to everything else. It’s what the French philosopher Pierre Hadot has referred to as the “oceanic feeling.” There is no ego standing beneath the giant redwoods or on the edge of a cliff or next to the crashing waves of the ocean.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>11. Choose alive time over dead time. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>According to author Robert Greene, there are <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://thoughtcatalog.com/ryan-holiday/2014/09/alive-time-vs-dead-time/" target="_blank">two types of time</a> in our lives: dead time, when people are passive and waiting, and alive time, when people are learning and acting and utilizing every second. During failure, ego picks dead time. It fights back: <em>I don’t want this. I want ______. I want it my way. </em>It indulges in being angry, aggrieved, heartbroken. Don’t let it — choose alive time instead.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>12. Get out of your own head. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Writer Anne Lamott knows the dangers of the soundtrack we can play in our heads: “The endless stream of self-aggrandizement, the recitation of one’s specialness, of how much more open and gifted and brilliant and knowing and misunderstood and humble one is.” That’s what you could be hearing right now. Cut through that haze with courage and live with the tangible and real, no matter how uncomfortable.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>13. Let go of control. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The poisonous need to control everything and micromanage is usually revealed with success. Ego starts saying: it all must be done my way — even little things, even inconsequential things. The solution is straightforward. A smart man or woman must regularly remind themselves of the limits of their power and reach. It’s simple, but not easy.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>14. Place the mission and purpose above you. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>During World War II, General George Marshall, winner of the Nobel Peace Prize for the Marshall Plan, was practically offered the command of the troops on D-Day. Yet he told President Roosevelt: “The decision is yours, Mr. President; my wishes have nothing to do with the matter.” It came to be that Eisenhower led the invasion and performed with excellence. Marshall put the mission and purpose above himself — an act of selflessness we need to remind ourselves of.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>15. When you find yourself in a hole — stop digging. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“Act with fortitude and honor,” Alexander Hamilton wrote to a distraught friend in serious trouble of the man’s own making. “If you cannot reasonably hope for a favorable extrication, do not plunge deeper. Have the courage to make a full stop.” Our ego screams and rattles when it is wounded. We will then do <em>anything </em>to get out of trouble. Stop. Don’t make things worse. Don’t dig yourself further. Make a plan.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>16. Don’t be deceived by recognition, money and success — stay sober. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Success, money, and power can intoxicate. What is required in those moments is sobriety and a refusal to indulge. One look at Angela Merkel, one of the most powerful women on the planet is revealing. She is plain and modest — one writer said that unpretentiousness is Merkel’s main weapon — unlike most world leaders intoxicated with the position. Leave self-absorption and obsessing over one’s image for the egotists.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>17. Leave your entitlement at the door.</strong> </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Right before he destroyed his own billion-dollar company, Ty Warner, creator of Beanie Babies, overrode the objections of one of his employees and bragged, “I could put the Ty heart on manure and they’d buy it!” You can see how this manifestation of ego can lead you to success — and how it can lead to downright failure.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>18. Choose love. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Martin Luther King understood that hate is like an “eroding acid that eats away the best and the objective center of your life.” Hatred is when ego turns a minor insult into a massive sore and it lashes out. But pause and ask: has hatred and lashing out ever helped anyone with <em>anything</em>? Don’t let it eat at you — choose love. Yes, love. See how much better you feel.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>19. Pursue mastery in your chosen craft. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>When you are <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://thoughtcatalog.com/ryan-holiday/2016/05/44-writing-hacks-from-some-of-the-greatest-writers-who-ever-lived/" target="_blank">pursuing a craft</a> you realize that the better you get, the humbler you are. Because you understand there’s always something you can learn and you are inherently humbled by this fascinating craft or career you’re after. It is hard to get a big head or become egotistical when you’ve decided on that path.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>20. Keep an inner scorecard. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Just because you won doesn’t mean you deserved to. We need to forget other people’s validation and external markers of success. Warren Buffett has advised keeping an inner scorecard versus the external one. <mark>Your potential, the absolute best you’re capable of — that’s the metric to measure yourself against.</mark></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>21. Paranoia creates things to be paranoid about. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>“He who indulges empty fears earns himself real fears,” wrote Seneca, who as a political adviser witnessed destructive paranoia at the highest levels. If you let ego think that everyone is out to get you you will seem weak…and then people will really try to take advantage of you. Be strong, confident, and forgiving.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>22. Always stay a student. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Put yourself in rooms where you’re the least knowledgeable person. Observe and learn. That uncomfortable feeling, that defensiveness that you feel when your most deeply held assumptions are challenged? Do it <em>deliberately</em>. Let it humble you. Remember how the physicist John Wheeler put it, “As our island of knowledge grows, so does the shore of our ignorance.”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>23. No one can degrade you — they degrade themselves. </strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Ego is sensitive about slights, insults, and not getting their due. This is a waste of time. After Frederick Douglass was asked to ride in a baggage car because of his race, someone rushed to apologize for this mistreatment. Frederick’s reply? “They cannot degrade Frederick Douglass. The soul that is within me no man can degrade. I am not the one that is being degraded on account of this treatment, but those who are inflicting it upon me.”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>24. Stop playing the image game — focus on a higher purpose.</strong> </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>One of the best strategists of the last century, John Boyd, would ask the promising young acolytes under him: “To be or to do? Which way will you go?” That is, will you choose to fall in love with the image of how success looks like or will you focus on a higher purpose? Will you pick obsessing over your title, the number of fans, the size of a paycheck, or on real, tangible accomplishment? You know which way the ego wants to go.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>25. Focus on the effort — not the results.</strong> </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>This is so important it is appearing twice. If you can accept that you control only the effort that goes in and <a rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank" href="https://medium.com/the-mission/heres-why-you-re-the-only-one-who-gets-to-define-what-success-is-157968e0c0fc">not the results which come out,</a> you will be mastering your ego. All work leaves our hands at some point. Ego wants to control everything — but it cannot control other people or their reactions. Focus on your end of the equation, leave them to theirs. Remember Goethe’s line: “What matters to an active man is to do the right thing; whether the right thing comes to pass should not bother him.”</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->]]></content:encoded>

<p class="has-text-color has-very-light-gray-color">Every drop Yumyoda has done came with limited edition stickers. These are stickers which vary in culture, and celebrate not just the impact each had in their own way, but also the diversity in the collection. Every single one of us are displayed on these stickers. Every single one of us inspires the next when we make bold choices and challenge what is considered the status quo. </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>These stickers are especially made for backers of the SEPTEMBER SEED Kickstarter Campaign</p>

<div class="wp-block-group"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container"><!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->
<h4>X and King Only Met Once</h4>
<!-- /wp:heading --></div></div>
<!-- /wp:group -->

<!-- wp:group -->
<div class="wp-block-group"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container"><!-- wp:paragraph -->

<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div></div>
<!-- /wp:group -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":3065,"sizeSlug":"large","className":"is-style-default"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large is-style-default"><img src="http://www.yumyoda.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/stickers-stack-bo-r1-malcolm-x-martin-luther-king-jr-1024x341.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-3065"/></figure>

<div class="wp-block-group"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container"><!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->
<h4>X</h4>
<!-- /wp:heading --></div></div>
<!-- /wp:group -->

<!-- wp:group -->
<div class="wp-block-group"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container"><!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><a href="https://www.history.com/topics/black-history/malcolm-x">https://www.history.com/topics/black-history/malcolm-x</a></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div></div>
<!-- /wp:group -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":3066,"sizeSlug":"large","className":"is-style-default"} -->

<div class="wp-block-group"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container"><!-- wp:heading {"level":4} -->
<h4>Between Two Brothers (A)</h4>

					</item>
					<item>
		<title></title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/?p=3195</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 05 Dec 2020 01:46:13 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.yumyoda.com/?p=3195</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>I think it's important for many, including those in the mix, to understand what it means to contribute toward a movement. I mean those, or we, who at this point - with no judgement of oneself, have some disagreements with either a tactic or message. I believe, that the Black Lives Matter movement is one that has been most at resourceful at not just opening the eyes to the bruises, cuts, and fractions of society... but also, in a manor which is creative. </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>While I've only experienced the movements of the past through videography and cinematography, it does seem like we've been fighting for the same Social Justice for a very long time. The movement, by a witness, and creative has been all too well like the fight we've been dealing with within ourselves. Is that the reason we're drawn to this autonomic wave, actively tending to the pain? Because we know it all so well and where it's coming from or is it because it's a calling to a Hero's Journey? </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>
		<wp:post_id>3195</wp:post_id>
		<wp:post_date><![CDATA[2020-12-05 01:46:13]]></wp:post_date>
		<wp:post_date_gmt><![CDATA[2020-12-05 01:46:13]]></wp:post_date_gmt>
		<wp:comment_status><![CDATA[open]]></wp:comment_status>
		<wp:ping_status><![CDATA[open]]></wp:ping_status>
		<wp:post_name><![CDATA[__trashed-6]]></wp:post_name>
		<wp:status><![CDATA[trash]]></wp:status>
		<wp:post_parent>0</wp:post_parent>
		<wp:menu_order>0</wp:menu_order>
		<wp:post_type><![CDATA[post]]></wp:post_type>
		<wp:post_password><![CDATA[]]></wp:post_password>
		<wp:is_sticky>0</wp:is_sticky>
										<category domain="category" nicename="uncategorized"><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
						<wp:postmeta>
		<wp:meta_key><![CDATA[_wp_trash_meta_status]]></wp:meta_key>
		<wp:meta_value><![CDATA[draft]]></wp:meta_value>
		</wp:postmeta>
							<wp:postmeta>
		<wp:meta_key><![CDATA[_wp_trash_meta_time]]></wp:meta_key>
		<wp:meta_value><![CDATA[1607132773]]></wp:meta_value>
		</wp:postmeta>
							<wp:postmeta>
		<wp:meta_key><![CDATA[_wp_desired_post_slug]]></wp:meta_key>
		<wp:meta_value><![CDATA[]]></wp:meta_value>
		</wp:postmeta>
							<wp:postmeta>
		<wp:meta_key><![CDATA[_vp_words_count]]></wp:meta_key>
		<wp:meta_value><![CDATA[172]]></wp:meta_value>
		</wp:postmeta>
							</item>
					<item>
		<title></title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/?p=3325</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 05 Dec 2020 01:46:13 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.yumyoda.com/?p=3325</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>NYPD alone has spent over 200 Million Taxpayer Dollars Per Year on Police Misconduct and Corruption. The U.S. spends a collective $100 billion on policing per year and another $80 billion on incarceration. $5 Million of that goes toward policing in NYC. NYPD has over 300,000 civilian complaints prior to 2014. This doesn't include the pending complaints. </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>A large number of people, though still not popular, say that Defunding the Police is the way to go... However, a smaller amount is saying to Abolish the police. The unpopularity can be because of a lack of education about defunding or abolishing the police and/or lack of direction in executing such demands... but to dismiss it as invalid undermines the scholars and the actual number of people who support the demand. </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The benefit of these strategies will be the new budget cities have in order to open opportunities through its communities to expand education, housing, and reconnecting healthy family affairs. We know crime is not random. We know there is a small number of mentally discoursed-bad people, but these are people who tend to take toward big crime as opposed to small and petty criminal acts that stem from missing opportunities. </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>When police officers misidentify what de-escalation means, and its effectiveness on countless altercations, skips all possible remedies to defuse an intense situation and takes the life of another human being - how can we justify it?</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The Cops Were Scared - This is the most common justification. It makes sense to the situation - However, no matter who we're speaking to, it is safe to say Police Officers are the people others call to handle such situations. Excepting this to be a justified reality would mean that calling the police on anyone having an advanced psychological breakdown is technically making a call from one fearful person to another fearful person. And although this leaves room for cynical population control humor, if I'd had to pick what kind of Police I would want, it wouldn't be a fearful one. Those who pose that kind of power yet feel fearful are weak. Police should not be weak in this way. There are classes on confidence and assertiveness. </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The Cops Didn't Have The Tools - To date, the US has spent over $15 billion on the militarization of police. The 1033 and the 1122 initiatives. The 1122 program allows the police to purchase new military equipment using their own funding with the same discounts enjoyed by the federal government. The 1033 program allows the Department of Defense to transfer excess military equipment to local law enforcement agencies free of charge, as long as they pay for shipping and maintenance. Programs like this can inspire non-lethal tactical training as well as new programs where local police departments throughout the US can spread the weapons and tools. Defunding police isn't an excuse to increase deaths by police officers, its a calling to be smart.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->]]></content:encoded>

					<item>
		<title>Tre From Boyz In The Hood</title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/?p=4090</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 05 Dec 2020 01:46:13 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.yumyoda.com/?p=4090</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>In almost EVERY hood movie, there's a message. Gangstas being gangstas, but easily we overlook the message. we over-look the how and why.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Tre, from #BoyzInTheHood, represents all those friends who got a lucrative job, or moved out the hood, or got into politics, or joined the military, or even joined the fuck-boi12… Accept Tre, like very few, before ESCAPING - witnessed and understood first-hand how Oppressors exist. How they exist beyond drug dealers, how they exist beyond gang members, and how they exist beyond skin color.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The gun to the neck of this educated and refined brother's neck isn't an authority, isn't a black man, isn't just a senior to the community… The director, John Singleton, did this on purpose. Before you escape, before you build a safety net around yourself - just remember before you learn what privilege is… You once were in the hood… like Tre, like Treyvon, like Breonna, like many… too many. Oppressors don't like tough people. Oppressors don't like self-thinkers. If you're going to be something, do it fast and get out of here, and don't come back.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->]]></content:encoded>

					<item>
		<title>5 Things You Don&#039;t Compromise When Career Building</title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/?p=4108</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 05 Dec 2020 01:45:38 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.yumyoda.com/?p=4108</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Below are the top five things you should never compromise on while building your career (or you’ll regret it deeply):</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Your Standards of Integrity</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>I view “standards of integrity” as core principles and values that guide our behavior.&nbsp; Integrity is a choice, and while it is influenced by a myriad of factors (your culture, upbringing, peer influences, etc.), it can’t be forced.&nbsp; (If it is, you have played a part in that.)&nbsp; One who has strong and well-defined standards of integrity behaves with wholeness, integration, honesty, and does right by himself/herself and by others.&nbsp; Standards of integrity involve values and virtues such as honesty, kindness, trust, wisdom, loyalty, transparency, objectivity, acceptance, openness, empathy, and graciousness.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>I’ve seen so many people in midlife awaken as if from a long stupor to realize that they’ve compromised their most core values in order to get ahead in their work or keep jobs they hate.&nbsp; It hurts them to find that they’ve walked away from who they are, and what they value and cherish most.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>People mistakenly believe that in these tough recessionary times they have to give up on their values and integrity to stay employed, but that’s simply not true.&nbsp; Those who are guided by a strong sense of integrity fare much better in professional life and will be successful where others fail.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Your Self-Respect</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>I’ve personally lived through the heartache of compromising my self-respect to stay in a job. Years ago when I was a corporate marketing professional, I knew that how I was behaving (because I felt pressured to), was beneath me.&nbsp; I wasn’t the leader or manager I longed to be, because I couldn’t manage and navigate through the toxicity, stress, and overwhelm I felt in my job or in the organization.&nbsp; I tried to speak up about what I saw around me that wasn’t right, but I got crushed down.&nbsp; In the end, I completely lost my self-respect and felt that I was “prostituting” myself in order to keep my job and maintain my high salary.&nbsp; I knew literally in the first week that the job and company were wrong for me.&nbsp; What should I have done?&nbsp; Find a new job fast.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Your Soul for Money</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Money – and our relationship with it -- is a topic that’s spawned millions of books, articles, and seminars.&nbsp; Many of us struggle each day by maintaining a healthy balance and appropriate power dynamic with our money, and most of us fail.&nbsp; I’ve seen countless professionals give up their souls for money – not because they are struggling to pay the bills, but because they’ve become enslaved by their lifestyle and their need to impress.&nbsp; These folks have forgotten that they’ve come here at this time on this planet to do more than pay the bills, acquire things, and keep up with the Joneses.&nbsp; I’m not saying that fulfilling your financial obligations isn’t important – it is.&nbsp; I am saying that you are much more than your paycheck or bank account.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>You know if you’ve sacrificed your soul for money – it’s a painful, debilitating state that you can’t pretend your way out of.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>I know I'll hear from many of you who will say, "You're nuts.  I have to stay in this job I hate because I'm financially responsible for my family and it's the only job I can get."  Not knowing your situation, I can't say for sure, but my guess is that you absolutely do not have to work in ways you despise in order to do what's necessary for yourself and your family.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Your Health and Well-being</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>In my corporate training and seminars, I see hundreds of high-level professional women who are brilliant, achievement-oriented and accomplished, but at the same time exhausted, depleted, depressed, and demoralized.&nbsp; In the pursuit of a great career, they’ve compromised their health and well-being.&nbsp; Much of this has to do with the ever-complicated issue of&nbsp;work-life balance&nbsp;and how to stay competitive and ahead of the curve.&nbsp; But to me, it’s much more.&nbsp; Sacrificing your health and well-being demonstrates your lack of prioritizing yourself is important, failing to understand that you must care for yourself – and yes,&nbsp;put yourself first&nbsp;-- before you can be of true service to anyone else, your organization, your family or your employer.&nbsp; If your body is shutting down, diseased, or broken down from the way you work, rapid change is needed.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Your Legacy</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Finally, the saddest professionals I know have sacrificed their legacy in the process of building their careers.&nbsp; What is your legacy? It’s what you will be able to say about yourself when you’re 90 looking back -- what you’ve stood for, given, taught, imparted, and left behind. Not what you dreamed of being, but what you have been.&nbsp; It’s the impact you’ve made on the world, your family, and your community.&nbsp; This is not a dress rehearsal, but the real thing here, and so many professionals forget that they have this one chance to build a life that’s meaningful for them.&nbsp;&nbsp; Instead, they compromise their legacy in a vain effort to grasp “success,” accolades, security, or power.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>If you think you have to compromise on any of the above in order to be employed or build a successful career, I hope you’ll think again.&nbsp; I’ve lived and witnessed the pain of giving yourself up in the processing of creating a professional life, and despite all your best efforts, it will never bring you the success, fulfillment and reward you long for.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->]]></content:encoded>

					<item>
		<title>trinity</title>
		<link>http://www.yumyoda.com/untitled-reusable-block-10/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 27 Nov 2020 13:38:54 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[user]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.yumyoda.com/untitled-reusable-block-10/</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:columns {"className":"morePadding"} -->
<div class="wp-block-columns morePadding"><!-- wp:column -->
<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"align":"center"} -->
<h2 class="has-text-align-center">COMFORT</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Comfort</strong> will become your new favorite shirt. Instead of truly focusing on price, we've kept in mind the price we pay when sweatshops hire children and underpaid adults. We've kept in mind the price we pay when we turn a cheek at harsh conditions. Yeah we know you want a good price, but we want to sleep well too, so that comfort you feel, it's from doing good... but also... because we provide softness. </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column -->
<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"align":"center"} -->
<h2 class="has-text-align-center">DURABILITY</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Rather you're purchasing a T-shirt or Sweatshirt, our available <strong>Durability</strong>&nbsp;will always be a special kind of garment. Balanced between tough and soft, we seek out always to increase the strength and function of this line, without cranking the price too high. We made this section especially for athletes, so keep a close lookout on this section if you move around.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:column -->

<!-- wp:column -->
<div class="wp-block-column"><!-- wp:heading {"align":"center"} -->
<h2 class="has-text-align-center">ARMOR</h2>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Our <strong>"Armor"</strong>&nbsp;priced garments are a superior type of&nbsp;<strong>Supima cotton</strong>. What makes&nbsp;Supima&nbsp;unique to other cotton is the extra-long staple fiber that gives the&nbsp;cotton&nbsp;its premium properties: Strength, Softness, and Color retention. Like all&nbsp;<strong>cotton</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>Supima cotton</strong>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<strong>sustainable</strong>, renewable, and biodegradable. All&nbsp;<strong>Armor</strong>&nbsp;selections can last for years and years, only becoming softer throughout use.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div>
<!-- /wp:column --></div>
<!-- /wp:columns -->]]></content:encoded>
